# Deterministic Environment Overlays for Computer-Use Agents

**Composable, text-only behavioral contracts for hardware + operating system simulation.**  
Zero runtime cost. Fully traceable. Designed to be ingested by LLMs or used for mental execution during agent development and debugging.

## The Problem

Computer-use (GUI) agents that rely on screenshots, vision models, and simulated input are notoriously flaky. Common failure modes include:

- Phantom clicks caused by DPI scaling mismatches
- Sudden latency or OOMs when VRAM pressure forces layer offloading
- Focus stealing, UAC interference, or Game Mode blocking input simulation
- Non-deterministic behavior under thermal/power throttling or QoS changes

Traditional testing requires spinning full VMs or running on the real desktop. This is slow, resource-heavy (especially with ComfyUI video generation or large local models), risky, and difficult to debug ("why did the click miss on step 7?").

## The Solution

Instead of (or alongside) heavy emulation, model only the **relevant subsystems** as precise, algebraic text specifications. These overlays act as a deterministic execution contract that an agent — or a developer — can reason over without ever executing code on real hardware.

The approach stacks three layers:

1. **Hardware VM** — VRAM budgets, thermal/power curves, memory hierarchy, CPU/GPU behavior under AI workloads (concrete high-end Windows desktop example included).
2. **OS VM** — DPI coordinate math, input stack (SendInput), UI Automation, power/QoS policies, security surface, multi-monitor handling.
3. **Deterministic Overlay Spec** — Composition rules, threshold triggers, latency/quantization fallbacks, reliability engine mapping, and the overall value proposition.

When composed, these layers give you:
- Exact traceability (`IF VRAM ≥ 14.2 GB + Balanced QoS → 2.8× latency + force quantize`)
- Pre-flight simulation of long agent loops
- LLM-native specs you can feed directly into prompts
- Easy generation of deterministic failure-injection test cases

## Why This Matters

- **Zero runtime cost** — Simulate dozens of edge cases in seconds.
- **Traceable failures** — Turn "the agent was unreliable" into "threshold X was crossed at step N, triggering Y fallback."
- **Safer development** — Catch logic bugs before any real clicks or long-running GPU jobs.
- **Composability** — Add new layers (agent loop rules, specific app behaviors) without rewriting everything.
- **Especially valuable** when full VMs are impractical: resource-constrained machines, air-gapped environments, early logic iteration, or high-fidelity simulation of partial-offload inference scenarios.

This is a practical engineering pattern that synthesizes ideas from deterministic simulation testing (DST), lightweight GUI agent environments, and formal behavioral contracts — tailored specifically for local LLM + computer-use agent development on consumer/high-end Windows hardware.

